---

#### install

This time, I will also install `@ngneat/elf-personist-state` to save data in session storage.

`` `zsh
$ npm i @ngneat/elf @ngneat/elf-personist-state
`` `

---

#### Implementation

Unlike AKITA, it is possible to operate only in the following description, rather than injecting and using files using CLI.

- `Shared/Page.repository.ts`

`` `TS
Import {Createstore, Withprops} from '@ngneat/Elf';
Import {Persiststate, SessionStorageStrategy} from '@ngneat/Elf-personist-State';

Interface State {
  Location: Number;
}

CONST PAGESTORE = Createstore ({name: 'Pagestore'}, withprops <STATE> ({Location: 0}));

Persiststate (Pagestore, {Key: 'Page', Storage: SessionStorageStrategy});

Export Class Pagestate {
  Location = pagestore.getValue (). local;

  Update (Key: Keyof State, Value: Any) {
    Pagestore.Update ((state) => ({
      ... state,
      [Key]: Value,
    }));
  }
}
`` `

---

#### thoughts

I was impressed that the AKITA structure (Service, Store, Query) is easy to understand, but it is easy to handle ELF.

We plan to test around HTTP requests this time.

I thought it might be a bit painful about the transition of the project so far, as to whether it will be completely shifted to ELF, -1620967) seems to be maintained.
